"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769918","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-10-17T16:32:22.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769918/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769918/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Ministry of Justice: Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 105820, if he will make public applications made to the Government property unit to extend or renew their lets in each year since 2012 which were granted with conditions attached to them; and what the conditions were in each case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","107568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769919","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-19","<p>I am clear that we need to look across the entire family justice system to make sure it is delivering the best outcomes for children and families, and protecting its most vulnerable users. We are working to consider what further changes are needed and will bring forward our proposals in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-19T16:39:01.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769919/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769919/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Family Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the timetable is for the publication of the Government's Green Paper on family justice.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","107456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769920","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>There have been 2336 National Probation Staff who have been affected by the recent problems relating to pensions contributions. There are currently no plans to compensate these staff.</p><p> </p><p>There is a regular governance structure in relation to the provision of Shared Services, which reviews the service delivery of our provider, Shared Services Connected Limited to the Department. These mechanisms regularly review issues and incidents and have fully managed the recent issues in relation to pension contributions. These mechanisms have been effective in the management and closure of the defects.</p><p> </p><p>Following the migration of the departments HR and payroll data to the new cross government Single Operating Platform a small number of defects have been identified and corrected. These led to the under-collection of pension contributions for some staff. These have been corrected with the final correction being applied for inclusion in this month’s payroll and the full contributions have been paid to the pension scheme administrator. The contribution under collection only affected 4 types of overtime rate and 2 absence scheme calculations with the remaining payroll elements all being subject to the correct pensions deduction. The departments migration to the Single Operating Platform was subject to formal programme control and governance and these programme mechanisms have been used to resolve these issues.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","107439 ; 107440","2017-10-18T16:14:54.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769920/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769920/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","National Probation Service for England and Wales: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the reasons for administrative errors made by shared services which has resulted in no pension contributions being taken from the salary of probation service staff.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","107460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769921","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-19","<p>Information on meeting venues is not collected centrally and could not be obtained without incurring disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>In any case where a venue outside the probation estate is being considered, the offender manager is required to make an assessment, to determine whether the venue is appropriate.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-10-19T11:57:04.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769921/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769921/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Probation: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders currently meet their probation officer in a public space such as a library, café or restaurant due to a lack of appropriate space in probation offices.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","107607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769922","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-19","<p>In her report, the Chief Inspector of Probation found that the work of probation services in Cumbria was good, with exceptional practice at the CRC, and that the work of the CRC was the best they had seen since the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that it is important that offenders and probation staff can meet in an environment appropriate for their specific needs, and that public safety also forms part of those considerations. I expect the CRC to take note of, and act on the Chief Inspector’s recommendations. Our contract management teams will continue to monitor and robustly manage providers closely to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","107603 ; 107604","2017-10-19T15:58:27.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769922/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769922/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Probation: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the criticism of the use of booths in probation work contained in the HM Inspectorate of Probation report, The effectiveness of probation work in Cumbria, published in October 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","107592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769923","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-19","<p>In her report, the Chief Inspector of Probation found that the work of probation services in Cumbria was good, with exceptional practice at the CRC, and that the work of the CRC was the best they had seen since the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that it is important that offenders and probation staff can meet in an environment appropriate for their specific needs, and that public safety also forms part of those considerations. I expect the CRC to take note of, and act on the Chief Inspector’s recommendations. Our contract management teams will continue to monitor and robustly manage providers closely to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","107592 ; 107604","2017-10-19T15:58:27.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769923/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769923/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the settings used by community rehabilitation companies to meet service users; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","107603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769924","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-19","<p>In her report, the Chief Inspector of Probation found that the work of probation services in Cumbria was good, with exceptional practice at the CRC, and that the work of the CRC was the best they had seen since the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that it is important that offenders and probation staff can meet in an environment appropriate for their specific needs, and that public safety also forms part of those considerations. I expect the CRC to take note of, and act on the Chief Inspector’s recommendations. Our contract management teams will continue to monitor and robustly manage providers closely to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","107592 ; 107603","2017-10-19T15:58:27.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769924/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769924/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Probation: Meetings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on public safety of the use of booths by probation services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","107604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769925","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Department’s priority for the REFIT review is the correction of the scope of the Directive following the Vnuk judgment, such that it only applies to motor vehicles used in traffic. We collaborated with like-minded Member States to write a letter to the Commissioner putting forward this view.</p><p> </p><p>The Department continue to encourage UK stakeholders to talk with their counterparts in Europe.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is otherwise broadly content with how the Directive works but have made minor suggestions for improvement.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-20T12:47:43.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769925/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769925/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-12","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the options under consideration in the European Commission's consultation on the REFIT review of Directive 2009/103/EC on motor insurance; and what representations he is making to the (a) European Commission and (b) his EU counterparts on that matter.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","107500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769926","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-18","<p>The Government said, following the Supreme Court’s judgment in the case of R (Unison) v the Lord Chancellor, that it would put in place as soon as possible arrangements to refund those people who had paid fees in the Employment Tribunals.</p><p>We will announce the detailed arrangements shortly.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-18T14:21:06.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769926/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769926/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-12","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the timetable is for the reimbursement of employment tribunal fees; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","107570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769927","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>DWP have transferred this PQ to Cabinet Office for a response. In reply to question 105820, Cabinet Office stated that GPU does not release the specific detail relating to individual applications for expenditure as these are commercially sensitive. It would be the applicant department’s decision as to whether to release this information.</p><p> </p><p>GPU have contacted DWP asking whether they would grant permission to publish the information on DWP's behalf. DWP have stated that their policy is that they do not publish these figures as it might undermine or jeopardise the commercial process.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-23T14:30:21.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769927/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769927/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 105820, if he will make public applications made to the Government property unit to extend or renew their lets in each year since 2012 which were granted with conditions attached to them; and what the conditions were in each case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","107569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769928","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-19","<p>Within the last 12 months, the average length of time for a telephone call to the Department for Work and Pensions’ 0345 telephone lines was 11 minutes 29 seconds.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-19T13:02:39.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769928/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769928/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time of a call was to 0345 telephone numbers by his Department.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","107626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769929","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-17","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not hold this data.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-17T09:42:54.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769929/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769929/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average charge applied to mobile telephones calling 0345 numbers is.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","107551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769930","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-23","<p>We do not hold data relating to the number of cases where incorrect RTI data was found to result in an incorrect Universal Credit award.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-23T15:36:03.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769930/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769930/answer","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769930/answer/previousversion/15719","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many reports of incorrect universal credit awards investigated by HM Revenue and Customs and his Department Jointly Managed Engagement Team have been found attributable to Real Time Information data.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","107557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769931","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-23","<p>The system operated by HMRC and DWP to provide earnings details from employers and automatically include these in Universal Credit calculations is working well. Our internal data for September 2017 shows that only 0.4% of UC customers query the earnings used in their award, and the majority of these queries are resolved by explaining how Universal Credit works.</p><p>In September 2017, Universal Credit used over 360,000 separate earnings notifications in Universal Credit awards. In that same month just 1347 queries were investigated by DWP with just 238 being referred to HMRC Jointly Managed Engagement Team.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-23T15:39:45.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769931/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769931/answer","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769931/answer/previousversion/15717","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many reports of incorrect universal credit awards have been investigated by HM Revenue and Customs and his Department Jointly Managed Engagement Team.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","107556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769932","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-19","<p>Sanctions are only used in a minority of cases when people fail to meet each of their requirements that they agreed in their Claimant Commitment without good reason.</p><p> </p><p>We have a well-established system of hardship payments, available as a safeguard if a claimant demonstrates that they cannot meet their immediate and most essential needs, including accommodation, heating, food and hygiene, as a result of their sanction.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-19T12:59:59.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769932/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769932/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Social Security Benefits: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to assist households facing debt as a result of benefit sanctions.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","107618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769933","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-21","<p>The policy intention is that claimants receive the first payment 5 weeks after their date of entitlement (6 weeks if waiting days are served). The assessment period runs for a full calendar month from the date of entitlement, and the UC pay date will be 7 calendar days after the end of the assessment period. This mirrors the world of work and allows for a 1 month period in which to gather information about a claimants’ earnings. Advances and budgeting support are available to support claimants during this period. Advances can provide up to 50% of a claimant’s indicative award straight away.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Data published on 2 October 2017 shows that, in June 2017 81% of new Universal Credit households received their first payment in full and on time. Across the whole of Universal Credit 92% of all households received full payment on time.</p><p> </p><p>Our internal data shows that for those cases where full payment has not been made, around a sixth have not signed their Claimant Commitment or passed identity checks and the others have outstanding verification issues, e.g. housing, self-employed earnings and child-care costs.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-21T15:08:07.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769933/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769933/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Social Security Benefits: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to assist households facing debt as a result of social security delays.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","107619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769934","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-19","<p>The nationality and immigration status of claimants is not currently recorded on benefit payment systems. However the Department for Work and Pensions has published statistics on working age benefit recipients by nationality at point of National Insurance Number (NINo) registration. This is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/nationality-at-point-of-nino-registration-of-dwp-working-age-benefit-recipients-data-to-feb-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/nationality-at-point-of-nino-registration-of-dwp-working-age-benefit-recipients-data-to-feb-2017</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/analysis-of-migrants-access-to-income-related-benefits" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/analysis-of-migrants-access-to-income-related-benefits</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-10-19T12:38:31.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769934/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769934/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Social Security Benefits: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many non-UK EU citizens are in receipt of each of his Department's benefit to which they are entitled.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","107582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769935","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-17","<p>We will consider whether a claimant meets the criteria for stopping routine assessments as part of our existing WCA process, which involves assessing individuals against a set of functional descriptors to determine how their illness or disability affects their ability to work. The criteria are being considered as part of a claimant’s initial or next WCA.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-10-17T14:07:09.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769935/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769935/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Work Capability Assessment: Exemptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the response by the Minister of State for Disabled People, Health and Work of 12 September 2017 to the letter from the hon. Member for Edinburgh East, on stopping of repeated work capability assessments for people who have lifelong, progressive, degenerative or incurable conditions, how that status will be determined; and whether people with such conditions who are already in receipt of employment and support allowance will be required to undergo a further work capability assessment to determine that status.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","107522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769936","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-10-17","<p>In the last 12 months the total number of calls to the Department for Work and Pensions’ 0345 telephone lines was 37,127,041.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-10-17T10:02:18.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769936/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769936/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-10-12","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many calls to 0345 numbers his Department has received in the last year.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","107552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769937","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-24","<p>The joint government-industry Industrial Decarbonisation and Energy Efficiency Roadmap Action Plans for seven energy intensive sectors were published on 12 October 2017, alongside the Clean Growth Strategy. The Action Plans set out voluntary commitments from industry, government and third parties to enable the sectors to decarbonise and improve their energy efficiency, and provide a framework for continued government-industry joint working on decarbonisation and energy efficiency matters.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-10-24T12:07:30.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769937/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769937/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769937/answer/previousversion/15620","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-12","Energy Intensive Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to discuss industrial decarbonisation and energy efficiency action plans with the leaders of the seven most energy intensive industries.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","107506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769938","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-10-23","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has made one application to extend or to renew a lease since 2012. A new lease was agreed from 3 February 2013 for the Ground Floor, The Observatory in Chatham.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-10-23T10:50:32.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769938/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769938/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-10-12","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Government Property Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 October 2017 to Question 105820, if he will make public applications made to the Government property unit to extend or renew their lets in each year since 2012 which were granted with conditions attached to them; and what the conditions were in each case.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","107562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769939","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-23","<p>We are considering in depth our future trading relationships with a broad range of partners as we prepare to leave the EU. As set out in the Government’s Trade White Paper ’Preparing for our future UK trade policy’ the UK will look to secure greater access to overseas markets for UK goods exports as well as push for greater liberalisation of global services, investment and procurement markets.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-10-23T14:23:13.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769939/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769939/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-12","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which key targets for UK exports he has identified as a priority for future trade negotiations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","107571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769940","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-10-20","<p>The UK Government is committed to delivering as seamless and frictionless a border as possible between Northern Ireland and Ireland, recognising the unique significance of the Irish land border and the highly-integrated nature of trade across it, including in agricultural products, because it is in the interests of the EU and all parts of the UK for the deeply integrated trade and economic relationship between the UK and EU to be maintained after our exit from the EU. This can be consistent with pursuing independent trade deals and the Government set out principles and proposals for doing so in our Northern Ireland position paper. We have also always been clear that our guiding principle will be to ensure that as we leave the EU no new barriers to living and doing business within the UK are created. I will make statements on the range of issues on agricultural trade over the course the negotiations.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-10-20T13:58:14.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769940/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769940/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-10-12","Trade Agreements: Agricultural Products","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations he has received on the potential demerits of any trade deal that permits agricultural products to be traded on an all-Ireland basis; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","107572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769941","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-20","<p>The Department is committed to building a global Britain which champions free trade, where the government plays an important role in supporting trade and investment.</p><p> </p><p>Our objective is to focus HMG support to those foreign direct investment projects which will maximise wealth creation across the country.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside other government departments we are developing proposals in the HMG Industrial Strategy White paper that will improve the business environment for investment and align support to investments likely to have the greatest impact to the UK economy.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-20T13:57:54.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769941/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769941/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-12","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of what constitutes good practice in attracting foreign direct investment to the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","107620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769942","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-18","<p>We remain committed to increasing UK exports around the world. Following the creation of the Department for International Trade (DIT), and the establishment of a network of 9 overseas Trade Commissioners, we are reviewing our performance metrics to ensure they remain fit for purpose in an evolving landscape.</p><p>We will use our world leading digital offer to equip exporters with the tools they need to take advantage of a world of opportunity, and use DIT’s presence in 108<br>countries to promote British products and services, whilst removing trade barriers and increasing market access.</p><p /><p />","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-10-18T16:57:19.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769942/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769942/answer","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769942/answer/previousversion/15709","Biography information for Mark Garnier","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-12","Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether the UK is on course to meet the target to export £1 billion of goods and services by 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","107560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769943","Department for International Trade","false","2017-10-23","<p>In relation to EU Regulation 2017/1480 imposing anti-dumping duties on certain types of cast iron products, officials have received representations from three importers, of which they have met two, as well as representations from one group of European producers, which includes one UK producer.</p><p>In terms of analysing the effect of these regulations, the UK government examines all trade defence cases carefully and judges each on its own merits. This is based on an economic evaluation of the evidence presented in the European Commission’s draft regulation sent to Member States with any proposal for measures, together with information received from interested parties, including producers, importers and users of the product.</p><p>The Commission’s anti-dumping investigation concerning imports of cast iron articles from China and India is ongoing, and yet to make its final proposals. Officials have not made representations to the Commission at this stage in the investigation.</p><p>This is one of several trade defence measures which are being applied by the EU which affect UK industry. The Government is looking into the detail of UK trade remedies policy as a whole as we leave the EU. The Government is seeking to maintain continuity for businesses as we exit from the EU. We invite responses to the consultations launched as part of the Department’s recently published White Paper: ‘Preparing for our future UK trade policy’.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","107501 ; 107542 ; 107543 ; 107544 ; 107545 ; 107546 ; 107731","2017-10-23T07:48:25.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769943/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/769943/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-12","Iron and Steel: China","1","House of Commons","To ask 