"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767947","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Home Office does not set the fee for the settlement and nationality checking services. These fees are set locally by individual local authorities under their wellbeing provisions.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T16:37:24.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767947/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767947/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","Immigration: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment was made by the Home Office prior to setting fees for (1) the settlement checking service, and (2) the nationality checking service.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL1866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767948","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Home Office does not set the fee for the settlement checking service. These fees are set locally by individual local authorities under their wellbeing provisions.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T15:46:48.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767948/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767948/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","Immigration: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of fees set by the Home Office for settlement checking services at local councils was used to fund the delivery of those services in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL1867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767949","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Home Office does not set the fee for the nationality checking service. These fees are set locally by individual local authorities under their wellbeing provisions.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T15:47:02.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767949/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767949/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","British Nationality: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of fees set by the Home Office for nationality checking services at local councils was used to fund the delivery of those services in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL1868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767950","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>Fees received by the Home Office in respect of Citizenship applications are not used to fund the Nationality Checking Service. This service is offered by Local Authorities who fund its provision from the fees they set.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T16:44:17.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767950/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767950/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","British Nationality: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what proportion of fees for citizenship set by the Home Office was used to fund the Home Office’s assessment of citizenship applications for those applications assessed by local councils using the nationality checking service in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767951","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Life in the UK Advisory Group provided key recommendations on establishing the current processes for those applying for, and being granted, British Citizenship. We have no plans to relaunch it.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T16:29:05.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767951/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767951/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","British Nationality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the case for relaunching a Life in the UK Advisory Group to reassess the effectiveness and impact of reforms such as the citizenship test and ceremony a decade after their launch.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767952","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Life in the UK test is based upon our handbook – Life in the UK: A Guide for New Residents – which is available for all applicants to study as part of their test preparation. It was revised substantively in 2013, and took into account feedback received from previous applicants and others who had provided comments on it. The content of the handbook moved away from statistics and related information and put the emphasis on British history, culture and democracy. The test questions were revised at this time to reflect the change in emphasis.</p><p> </p><p>We will consider whether it would be appropriate to make the test available in Cornish as part of the protected minority status.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL1872","2017-10-24T16:12:59.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767952/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767952/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","British Nationality: Assessments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consultation with naturalised citizens they undertook before launching the current Life in the UK citizenship test.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767953","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Life in the UK test is based upon our handbook – Life in the UK: A Guide for New Residents – which is available for all applicants to study as part of their test preparation. It was revised substantively in 2013, and took into account feedback received from previous applicants and others who had provided comments on it. The content of the handbook moved away from statistics and related information and put the emphasis on British history, culture and democracy. The test questions were revised at this time to reflect the change in emphasis.</p><p> </p><p>We will consider whether it would be appropriate to make the test available in Cornish as part of the protected minority status.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL1871","2017-10-24T16:13:00.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767953/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767953/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","British Nationality: Assessments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of granting Cornish protected minority status in relation to the Life in the UK citizenship test.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767954","Home Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>No assessment has been made of introducing English language proficiency exemptions for applicants because of nationality.</p><p>All those applying for indefinite leave to remain under a provision where knowledge of language and life in the UK (KoLL) is a requirement, and all those applying for naturalisation as a British citizen, must meet KoLL. Exemptions to this requirement are primarily based on the applicant’s inability to prepare for or sit the test. Where an applicant has a physical or medical condition which would make it unreasonable to expect them to undertake the test, they can be exempted. Exemptions also exist on the basis of age.</p><p>There are no exemptions from KoLL due to a person’s nationality. A person who is a national of a majority English-speaking country will, however, be able to use this to demonstrate that they meet the English language part of the KoLL requirement.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-10-24T16:28:39.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767954/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767954/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of introducing English language proficiency exemptions for applicants for Indefinite Leave to Remain or citizenship because of nationality.","false","Biography information for Baroness Smith of Basildon",,"Baroness Smith of Basildon","HL1873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767955","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-24","<p>Complaints made directly to the Commission are dealt with by its central contact centre and to collate information on the number relating to affiliates would involve reviewing each complaint individually at disproportionate cost. The Commission is not the lead regulatory authority for advertising or SMS messaging and consumer complaints are directed to the Advertising Standards Authority or Information Commissioner’s Office in the first instance.</p><p> </p><p>Gambling operators providing services to customers in Great Britain must be licensed by the Commission and are responsible for the actions of affiliates on their behalf. If an affiliate breaches licence conditions and codes of practice (LCCP) the operator will be held accountable.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-10-24T11:39:32.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767955/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767955/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-10","Gambling Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many complaints the Gambling Commission received in 2016 related to gambling affiliate activity.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL1874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767956","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-24","<p>The UK makes contributions to the EU budget as a whole, rather than financing individual projects or assets.</p><p> </p><p>The arrangements for withdrawal from the EU, including financial matters, will be a matter for the negotiations as part of the Article 50 process. The government is committed to working with the EU to determine a fair settlement for Britain’s exit and the best deal for UK taxpayers.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-10-24T12:59:52.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767956/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767956/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-10","EU Institutions: Buildings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have sought, or will seek, a valuation of the buildings and office spaces (1) owned, (2) rented, and (3) leased, by the EU wherever located; and what share of those assets have been financed by the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL1875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767957","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-20","<p>UK citizens are not normally detained in prison without charge. The number of UK citizens on remand awaiting trial as of 30 June 2017 was 5,242. It is not possible to state the numbers of these individuals who do not have a date set for trial because this data is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Individuals who are subject to extradition for charges brought by other jurisdictions can be held in prison pending extradition. As at 30 June 2017, the number of people in prison pending extradition was 105, of which 84 were non-UK EU nationals.</p><p>Foreign National Offenders (FNOs) who have served a sentence may continue to be held in prison beyond their sentence end date under immigration powers pending removal from the United Kingdom. As at 30 June 2017, the number of FNOs held in prison under immigration powers was 448 (including 122 non-UK EU nationals).</p><p> </p><p>The Government is absolutely committed to increasing the number of FNOs removed from our prisons, and any foreign national who comes to our country and is sentenced to prison should be in no doubt of our determination to deport them. Increasing removals is one of our top priorities and all FNOs sentenced to custody are referred to the Home Office at the earliest opportunity to be considered for deportation.</p>",,"Baroness Vere of Norbiton",,"2017-10-20T10:24:45.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767957/answer","Biography information for Baroness Vere of Norbiton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767957/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-10-10","Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many UK citizens are currently held in prisons in England and Wales (1) in detention without charge, and (2) without a date set for trial; and how many non-UK EU citizens are similarly detained.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL1876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>Under the EU arms embargo, the UK would not export military equipment to Israel if we believed that the ultimate end user destination would be Burma. Israel is not subject to the EU embargo.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-24T16:34:20.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767958/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-10","Israel: Burma","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their response to reports that Israel is continuing to sell weapons to Myanmar given that the EU and the US have both banned arms sales to that country.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767959","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The UK has repeatedly called on the Israeli authorities to halt proposals to demolish Khan al-Ahmar. Prior to the most recently scheduled Israeli High Court hearing on the matter on 25 September – subsequently postponed - our Embassy in Tel Aviv raised our concerns with the Israeli authorities on 24 September.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-10-24T16:37:10.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767959/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767959/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-10","Israel: Bedouin","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding the impending forcible removal of the Bedouin village of Khan al-Amar if the ruling of the Israeli Supreme Court is implemented.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767960","Home Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>This country has a proud history of allowing free speech, but the right to peaceful protest does not extend to harassment or threatening behaviour. The police have a range of powers to deal with any such acts.</p><p>Under the Public Order Act 1986, chief officers may impose conditions on assemblies to prevent serious public disorder, serious damage to property, serious disruption to the life of the community or when the purpose is to intimidate others to compel them not to do an act that they have a right to do.</p><p>The police also have dispersal powers (in public places) under the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014, and the Protection from Harassment Act 1997 includes criminal offences that protect individuals, who are conducting lawful activities, from harassment by protestors. How these powers are deployed and the tactics used to manage protests are operational matters for the police.</p><p>Public Space Protection Orders are tools which local authorities can use to stop people committing anti-social behaviour in a public place, applying restrictions to how that public space can be used. They cannot be used to prohibit static protests.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL1880","2017-10-23T15:58:20.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767960/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767960/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how they plan to prevent harassment and intimidation of women accessing abortion services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767961","Home Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>This country has a proud history of allowing free speech, but the right to peaceful protest does not extend to harassment or threatening behaviour. The police have a range of powers to deal with any such acts.</p><p>Under the Public Order Act 1986, chief officers may impose conditions on assemblies to prevent serious public disorder, serious damage to property, serious disruption to the life of the community or when the purpose is to intimidate others to compel them not to do an act that they have a right to do.</p><p>The police also have dispersal powers (in public places) under the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014, and the Protection from Harassment Act 1997 includes criminal offences that protect individuals, who are conducting lawful activities, from harassment by protestors. How these powers are deployed and the tactics used to manage protests are operational matters for the police.</p><p>Public Space Protection Orders are tools which local authorities can use to stop people committing anti-social behaviour in a public place, applying restrictions to how that public space can be used. They cannot be used to prohibit static protests.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL1879","2017-10-23T15:58:20.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767961/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767961/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-10","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to introduce the power to use public space protection orders to prevent the harassment and intimidation of women accessing abortion services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767992","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-16","<p>The Data Protection Bill, which recently received its second reading, will create a modern legal framework for the UK, suitable for the digital age, incorporating the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR). It will require either clearer and affirmative consent from individuals to be sought, or apply additional safeguards where data processing is allowed in the absence of consent. The Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) recently published draft guidance on consent under the GDPR; this can be found on the ICO's website - www.ico.org.uk.</p><p> </p><p>Under the new law where direct marketing by post involves the processing of personal data, data controllers will need a legal basis for such processing. Article 6 of GDPR lists a number of possible legal bases which in certain circumstances can be relied upon by data controllers. Where no other legal basis applies then the consent of the data subject will be required.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-16T14:42:21.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767992/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767992/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767992/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-10","Direct Marketing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the General Data Protection Regulation, (EU) 2016/679, requires consent for postal direct marketing to change from opt out to opt in; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","106928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767993","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-17","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I<br>have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-17T13:57:39.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767993/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767993/answer","PQ107034 (1).pdf","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/767993/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-10","Armed Forces: Census","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of including a question in the next census about membership of the armed forces community.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","107034"
